         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">On board of the "Assam" 3/1/78. ¶  ¶ Returning from West Australia, dear Mr Ramsay, I conduct here some correspondence on board of the mail-steamer, &amp; have thus the pleasure of resuming my communicati...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">78.01.03</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Edward Ramsay</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">ML MSS.562, Letters to E. P. Ramsay 1862-91, Mitchell Library, State Library of New South Wales, Sydney.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">On board of the "Assam" 3/1/78.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Returning from West Australia, dear Mr Ramsay, I conduct here some correspondence on board of the mail-steamer, &amp; have thus the pleasure of resuming my communications with you also. Mr Bentham has sent me the proof sheets of vol. VII of the Flora up to Palms and the allied orders;<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Palms are treated in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, pp. 132-47. </p>
               </note> he compbines<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>combines?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> the <name key="Livistona%20Ramsayi">Livistona Ramsayi</name> with a new <name key="Licuala">Licuala</name> described simultaneously by Wendland from Dalrymple's Gap.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
               </note> But neither myself nor Wendland or Bentham had the flowers; hence the genus cannot be determined with safety. To me the genus <name key="Licuala">Licuala</name> of Blume seems only a subgenus of Livistona. I had given many years ago all my palms to the great von Martius, who asked for them, among them was Dallachy's specimen (in fruit only) from Dalrymple's Gap.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>After the death of the great writer on palms,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Martius died in 1868.</p>
               </note> the specimens went to Wendland, who begged for them. They were thus transferred from Munich to Hanover and only a few months ago they came back.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The description of the leaves of the <name key="Licuala">Licuala</name> does not correspond with your drawing,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>See image in E. Ramsay to M, 16 July 1874, note 5, <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>i.e. 74-07-16_image01.jpg</p>
               </note> because Bentham describes Dallachy's leaves as "divided to more than half the length into truncate lobes."<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, p. 145.</p>
               </note> Of course many palms have their very old leaves or leaflets torn into lobes, while they are in a normal state entire. Can you manage with your usual circumspectness to obtain at last flowers of this beautiful palm, flowers <seg>♂</seg> &amp; <seg>♀</seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Do you know the title of any paper in the far North of Queensland, to which I could write, asking that miners &amp;c might secure palms specimens for scientific description</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Wishing you every happiness in the new year, I remain, dear Mr Ramsay,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">your regardful</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Licuala">Licuala</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Livistona%20Ramsayi">Livistona Ramsayi</name>
            </p>
         </div>
